  "prompt": "What are traditional British dishes?",
  "response": "British cuisine is often underestimated, but it boasts a rich history and some truly comforting and delicious dishes. Here's a breakdown of some traditional British dishes:\n\n**Classics & Main Courses:**\n\n*   **Fish and Chips:** Perhaps the most iconic British dish. Deep-fried battered fish (typically cod or haddock) served with thick-cut chips (French fries) and salt and vinegar.\n*   **Sunday Roast:** A cornerstone of British culture. Roasted meat (usually beef, lamb, pork, or chicken), served with roasted potatoes, vegetables (carrots, peas, broccoli, etc.), Yorkshire pudding, stuffing, and gravy.\n*   **Full English Breakfast:** A hearty morning meal consisting of fried eggs, bacon, sausages, baked beans, tomatoes, mushrooms, black pudding, and toast. Regional variations exist.\n*   **Shepherd's Pie/Cottage Pie:** Mincemeat (ground meat) topped with mashed potatoes and baked. Shepherd's pie traditionally uses lamb, while cottage pie uses beef.\n*   **Bangers and Mash:** Sausages (bangers) served with mashed potatoes and onion gravy. A simple yet satisfying meal.\n*   **Steak and Ale Pie:** A savory pie filled with tender chunks of beef slow-cooked in ale (beer), often with mushrooms and vegetables.\n*   **Cornish Pasty:** A folded pastry filled with beef, potatoes, swede (rutabaga), and onion. Originating in Cornwall.\n*   **Toad in the Hole:** Sausages baked in Yorkshire pudding batter.\n*   **Black Pudding:** A type of blood sausage. It can be grilled or fried.\n\n**Puddings & Desserts:**\n\n*   **Sticky Toffee Pudding:** A moist sponge cake made with dates, covered in a rich toffee sauce, often served with vanilla ice cream or custard.\n*   **Eton Mess:** A dessert consisting of crushed meringue, strawberries, and whipped cream.\n*   **Apple Crumble:** Baked apples topped with a crumbly topping made from flour, butter, and sugar. Often served with custard.\n*   **Spotted Dick:** A steamed suet pudding containing dried fruit (currants, raisins, etc.), traditionally served with custard.\n*   **Trifle:** A layered dessert consisting of sponge cake soaked in sherry, fruit, custard, and whipped cream.\n*   **Bread and Butter Pudding:** A baked custard dessert made with slices of buttered bread, often with raisins.\n*   **Crumble:** Similar to Apple Crumble but can be made with other fruits like rhubarb.\n\n**Snacks & Lighter Fare:**\n\n*   **Afternoon Tea:** A light meal typically eaten in the late afternoon, consisting of sandwiches (cucumber, egg and cress, etc.), scones with clotted cream and jam, and cakes.\n*   **Scones:** Small baked cakes, traditionally served with clotted cream and jam as part of afternoon tea.\n*   **Scotch Egg:** A hard-boiled egg wrapped in sausage meat, coated in breadcrumbs, and deep-fried.\n*   **Cheese and Pickle Sandwich:** A simple but popular sandwich made with cheddar cheese and chutney or pickle (a sweet and tangy relish).\n*   **Pork Pie:** A savory pie filled with seasoned pork.\n\n**Regional Specialities:**\n\n*   **Welsh Rarebit (Wales):** A savory cheese sauce served over toast.\n*   **Haggis (Scotland):** A savory pudding containing sheep's pluck (heart, liver, and lungs), minced with onion, oatmeal, suet, spices, and stock.\n*   **Soda Bread (Northern Ireland):** A quick bread made with baking soda instead of yeast.\n*   **Arbroath Smokie (Scotland):** A type of smoked haddock.\n*   **Melton Mowbray Pork Pie (England):** A pork pie from Melton Mowbray, known for its uncured pork and hand-formed pastry.\n*   **Bakewell Tart (England):**  A shortcrust pastry case filled with a layer of jam, frangipane (almond filling), and often topped with flaked almonds.\n\n**Things to keep in mind:**\n\n*   **Modern Influences:** While these are traditional dishes, many have evolved over time and are influenced by global cuisine.\n*   **Regional Variations:** Many dishes have regional variations, so what you find in one part of Britain might be slightly different in another.\n*   **Availability:** Some of these dishes are more commonly found in restaurants or pubs than in everyday home cooking, although many people still cook traditional meals at home, especially on weekends.\n\nEnjoy exploring the world of British cuisine!\n",
